-- #672 (S0, run != build): a COMPILE-TIME-CONSTANT NaN must sort/compare/hash
-- identically across all three engines on the SAME box.
--
-- `0.0 / 0.0` (and `x % 0.0`, NaN for any finite x) is a constant, so the native
-- (LLVM) backend emitted `fdiv`/`frem double 0.0, 0.0` and clang const-folded it
-- to APFloat's canonical qNaN = +NaN (0x7FF8...), while the tree-walk interpreter
-- and the WasmGC backend both computed the HOST's NaN at runtime -- -NaN
-- (0xFFF8...) on x86 (native runtime `divsd`/libm `fmod`; eval `floatRem = fmod`).
-- Under the sign-dependent totalOrder (N6, Rust total_cmp) a +NaN sorts/compares/
-- hashes OPPOSITELY to a -NaN, so `compare (0.0/0.0) 1.0` (and the `%` twin) was
-- `Gt` under `medaka build` but `Lt` under `medaka run` -- a silent same-box
-- run != build divergence.  The emitter now folds a constant NaN op on the host
-- (`/` via hardware fdiv, `%` via the same libm fmod the runtime uses) and emits
-- its exact bits, so native keeps the runtime's -NaN and all three engines agree.
--
-- Both `/` AND `%` are exercised: they take DIFFERENT emit paths (`fdiv` vs
-- `frem`/`mdk_float_rem`), so folding one does not cover the other -- the initial
-- #672 fix folded only `/` and left `%` as the identical open bug.
--
-- Unlike float_totalorder_nan.mdk (which states every NaN law RELATIVE to nanLow
-- and is therefore blind to a sign divergence), this fixture prints the RAW
-- sign-dependent results, so the engines differential SEES a divergence.
--
-- #509-SAFE: the engines gate diffs the three engines against EACH OTHER on the
-- same box (no golden file, and NO .pin for this fixture on purpose), so an x86
-- -NaN vs an arm +NaN never enters the comparison -- only same-box agreement does.

import list.{sort}

main = (
  compare (0.0 / 0.0) 1.0,
  compare (0.0 % 0.0) 1.0,
  debug (sort [2.0, 0.0 / 0.0, 5.0 % 0.0, 1.0]),
  hashFloat (0.0 / 0.0),
  hashFloat (0.0 % 0.0),
)
